ia production, media work, media management, and media industries.Specific topics highlighted:- the history of media industries and production studies;- production studies as a field and a research method;- changing media business models, economics, and management;- global concentration and convergence of media industries and professions;- the rise and role of startups and entrepreneurship;- freelancing in the digital age;- the role of creativity and innovation;- the emotional quality of media work;- diversity and inequality in the media industries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aFilm, Media and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aMedia industries.  acreativity.  ainnnovation.  amedia business.  amedia economics.  amedia labor.  amedia management.  amedia policy.  amedia production.  amedia work.  aprecarity.1 aBaker, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhroin, Niamh Ní, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilton, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolin, Göran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBosch, Tanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrouwers, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCantillon, Zelmarie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan-Olmsted, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Nicole S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeuze, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeuze, Mark, eeditor.4edt4